{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"de59b232-a786-4e59-bf64-beb0d7b1fe98","content":"In .NET MAUI, you configure platform lifecycle events in your `MauiProgram.cs` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.\n- The delegates receive the native platform object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS).\n- Other events are available too (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c1767df0-0415-4761-a7cf-94a93f657db7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI - specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":339,"requestId":"6C1A:30221B:7D29FA:85C2FB:6A0AF60A"},"id":"ec45fd30-35b4-43dd-b3dc-4c1573f249e6","timestamp":"2026-05-18T11:20:55.379Z","parentId":"ef747a3e-b3ba-451e-9ce6-dc42b2b73538"}
